VALUES
(44, 28, 1, 44, 27, 26, 26, NULL, 'Escape and Destination Connection', 'This connection highlights the journey of Paul and his companions as they escape from a shipwreck and find themselves on the island of Melita. The mention of being ''cast upon a certain island'' in Acts 27:26 anticipates their eventual arrival at Melita, linking the two passages.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 1, 44, 27, 44, 44, 'escaped', 'Escape and Arrival at Land', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of escape and survival. Acts 27:44 describes the means by which the individuals reached safety, while Acts 28:1 identifies the location where they landed after their escape.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 1, 44, 27, 39, 39, 'they knew that the island was called Melita', 'Discovery of Land', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of discovery regarding the land. In Acts 27:39, they do not know the land, while in Acts 28:1, they learn the name of the island, Melita.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 1, 44, 16, 10, 10, NULL, 'Journey and Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance in the journeys of Paul. In both passages, there is a sense of direction and purpose as they navigate their paths, whether escaping to Melita or going to Macedonia.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 45, 1, 14, 14, 'barbarous people', 'Connection of Barbarians in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the term ''Barbarians,'' highlighting the inclusion of diverse peoples in the early Christian mission. Acts 28:2 illustrates the kindness of the ''barbarous people,'' while Romans 1:14 acknowledges a debt to both Greeks and Barbarians, suggesting a shared humanity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 51, 3, 11, 11, 'barbarous people shewed us no little kindness', 'Connection of Kindness and Inclusion', 'This connection highlights the theme of kindness and acceptance across cultural boundaries. Both passages emphasize the idea that all people, regardless of their background, are valued in the community of Christ.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 58, 13, 2, 2, 'no little kindness', 'Kindness to Strangers', 'This connection highlights the theme of kindness and hospitality towards others. Both passages emphasize the importance of showing kindness to strangers, suggesting that such actions can have significant, even divine, implications.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 44, 28, 4, 4, 'no little kindness', 'Kindness and Judgment Theme', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the kindness shown by the barbarians in providing a fire and the subsequent judgment they express when they see Paul bitten by a snake. Both passages emphasize the barbarians'' initial hospitality followed by their quick shift to suspicion and judgment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 47, 11, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Cold and Hardship', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of cold, highlighting the physical challenges faced by Paul and his companions. In Acts, the cold prompts kindness from others, while in 2 Corinthians, it is listed among the hardships endured.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 20, 24, 11, 12, 'no little kindness', 'Kindness and Deliverance Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of kindness and the moral obligation to help others in need. Acts 28:2 describes the kindness shown to Paul and his companions, while Proverbs 24:11-12 emphasizes the importance of delivering those in peril. Both passages underscore the responsibility to act compassionately towards those facing danger.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 2, 40, 10, 42, 42, 'cold', 'Kindness and Hospitality Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of kindness and hospitality in both passages. Acts 28:2 describes the kindness shown by the people through their actions, while Matthew 10:42 emphasizes the reward for acts of kindness, even as simple as giving a cup of cold water.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 40, 23, 33, 33, 'viper', 'Connection of Serpents and Vipers', 'This connection highlights the imagery of serpents and vipers in both passages. In Acts, the viper attacks Paul, while in Matthew, Jesus condemns the Pharisees as vipers, emphasizing danger and malice.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 40, 12, 34, 34, NULL, 'Connection of Vipers in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the metaphorical use of ''vipers'' in both passages. In Acts, the viper represents danger and malice, while in Matthew, it symbolizes evil and hypocrisy in speech.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 44, 28, 4, 4, 'fastened on his hand', 'Paul''s Encounter with Danger', 'This connection highlights the immediate reaction of the barbarians to Paul''s situation after the viper fastened on his hand. Both passages emphasize the perception of Paul as a man marked by fate, suggesting that he has escaped one danger only to face another.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 47, 11, 23, 23, NULL, 'Paul''s Suffering and Resilience', 'This connection highlights Paul''s experiences of danger and survival. In Acts, he faces a viper, while in 2 Corinthians, he recounts his numerous hardships, emphasizing his resilience in ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 18, 20, 16, 16, 'viper', 'Connection of Vipers and Danger', 'This connection highlights the danger associated with vipers in both passages. In Acts, the viper bites Paul, while in Job, the viper''s poison is lethal, emphasizing the threat posed by these creatures.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 23, 30, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Vipers in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of vipers, symbolizing danger and adversity. In Acts, the viper attacks Paul, while Isaiah mentions vipers in a context of trouble and anguish.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 3, 23, 41, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Danger and Worthlessness', 'This connection highlights the theme of danger and the idea of worthlessness. In Acts, the viper represents a threat to Paul, while Isaiah emphasizes the futility of choosing worthless things.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 42, 13, 2, 2, 'murderer, whom, though he hath escaped', 'Judgment and Suffering Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment based on suffering. Both passages emphasize the belief that suffering is a sign of wrongdoing, as seen in the barbarians'' assumption about Paul and Jesus'' reference to the Galileans.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 43, 7, 24, 24, NULL, 'Judgment and Appearance', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment based on appearances. In Acts, the barbarians judge Paul as a murderer based on the snake bite, while John emphasizes the need for righteous judgment beyond mere appearances.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 44, 28, 2, 2, NULL, 'Kindness and Judgment Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrasting responses of the barbarians towards Paul. While they initially show kindness by kindling a fire, they later judge him as a murderer when the snake bites him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 23, 43, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Beasts and Honor', 'This connection highlights the presence of ''beast'' in both passages, where the barbarians associate a beast with judgment and Isaiah speaks of beasts honoring God. Both passages emphasize the significance of creatures in relation to divine actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 40, 23, 35, 35, 'murderer, whom, though he hath escaped', 'Judgment and Righteousness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment against those deemed guilty. In Acts, the barbarians assume the man is a murderer facing divine retribution, while in Matthew, Jesus speaks of the blood of the righteous being avenged.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 43, 9, 1, 2, 'murderer, whom, though he hath escaped', 'Judgment and Suffering Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and suffering in both passages. In Acts, the barbarians assume the man is a murderer due to his suffering, while in John, the disciples question whether sin caused the man''s blindness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 4, 1, 3, 1, 1, 'venomous beast', 'Connection of Serpent and Vengeance', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a dangerous creature, with the serpent in Genesis representing temptation and the venomous beast in Acts symbolizing judgment. This connection highlights the theme of danger associated with these creatures and the consequences of human actions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 42, 10, 19, 19, NULL, 'Power Over Harmful Creatures', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine protection against harm from dangerous creatures. Acts 28:5 illustrates this through Paul''s experience with a serpent, while Luke 10:19 promises power over serpents and scorpions, indicating a similar assurance of safety.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 41, 16, 18, 18, 'felt no harm', 'Divine Protection from Harm', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine protection against harm. In Acts 28:5, the shaking off of the beast signifies immunity from danger, while Mark 16:18 promises that believers will not be harmed by serpents or deadly substances.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 19, 91, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of overcoming dangerous creatures. Acts 28:5 illustrates protection from a serpent, while Psalms 91:13 speaks of treading upon dangerous animals.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 4, 21, 6, 9, 'felt no harm', 'Connection of Deliverance from Harm', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from danger. In both passages, individuals are saved from lethal threats—Paul from a snake bite and the Israelites from serpent bites through looking at the brass serpent.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 66, 9, 3, 4, 'felt no harm', 'Connection of Harm and Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection against harm. In Acts, the shaking off of the beast signifies immunity from danger, while in Revelation, the locusts are commanded not to harm those with God''s seal, emphasizing a protective barrier.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 43, 3, 14, 15, 'felt no harm', 'Connection of Deliverance and Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from harm. In Acts, the act of shaking off the beast signifies overcoming danger, while in John, belief in the Son of man leads to eternal life, suggesting a spiritual deliverance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 5, 45, 16, 20, 20, 'felt no harm', 'Victory Over Harm', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection and victory over evil. In Acts, the shaking off of the beast signifies overcoming danger, while Romans speaks of God bruising Satan, indicating triumph over malevolent forces.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 6, 44, 12, 22, 22, 'said that he was a god', 'Recognition of Divine Status', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to individuals they perceive as divine. In Acts 28:6, the crowd initially expects Paul to die but then declares him a god, while in Acts 12:22, the people shout that a voice they hear is that of a god.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 6, 40, 21, 9, 9, NULL, 'Recognition of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition of divine authority. In Acts, the people initially mistake Paul for a god after witnessing a miraculous event, while in Matthew, the crowds proclaim Jesus as the one sent from God, recognizing His authority.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 6, 44, 14, 11, 13, 'said that he was a god', 'Divine Recognition in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to miraculous events, leading them to declare Paul and Barnabas as gods. In Acts 28, the crowd initially expects harm to Paul but then changes their minds, similar to how the people in Acts 14 recognize divine presence in Paul and Barnabas.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 6, 40, 27, 22, 22, NULL, 'Perception of Divine Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of public perception regarding divine identity. In Acts, the people initially expect harm but then declare Paul a god, while in Matthew, the crowd insists on crucifying Jesus, revealing contrasting views on his divinity.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 40, 10, 40, 41, 'received us, and lodged us', 'Hospitality and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality, as both passages emphasize the importance of receiving others. In Acts, Publius receives Paul and his companions, paralleling the call in Matthew to receive those sent by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 42, 19, 6, 9, 'received us, and lodged us three days courteously', 'Hospitality and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality and reception in both passages. In Acts, Publius receives Paul and his companions courteously, while in Luke, Zaccheus joyfully receives Jesus, demonstrating a welcoming spirit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 44, 13, 7, 7, NULL, 'Leadership and Reception of the Gospel', 'Both passages emphasize the role of influential leaders who are receptive to the message of God. Publius and Sergius Paulus are depicted as key figures who welcome the apostles, facilitating the spread of the Gospel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 44, 18, 12, 12, 'chief man of the island', 'Leadership and Authority in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize figures of authority, with Publius as the chief man of the island and Gallio as the deputy of Achaia. This connection highlights the interactions Paul has with influential leaders during his ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 44, 23, 24, 24, NULL, 'Hospitality and Protection Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hospitality and protection. In Acts 28:7, Publius provides lodging, while Acts 23:24 mentions providing beasts for safe transport.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 7, 44, 28, 2, 2, NULL, 'Kindness of the Islanders', 'Both passages emphasize the kindness shown by the islanders to Paul and his companions. In Acts 28:2, the ''barbarous people'' kindle a fire, while in Acts 28:7, Publius receives them courteously, illustrating a theme of hospitality.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 44, 9, 40, 40, 'prayed', 'Healing and Resurrection Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing in both passages. Paul heals Publius''s father, while Peter raises Tabitha, demonstrating the power of prayer and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 41, 6, 5, 5, 'laid his hands on him', 'Healing Through Laying on Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands on the sick as a means of healing. In Acts, Paul heals Publius by laying hands on him, while in Mark, Jesus heals a few sick folk in a similar manner.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 40, 9, 18, 18, 'laid his hands on him', 'Healing through Laying on Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands as a means of healing. In Acts, Paul lays his hands on Publius to heal him, while in Matthew, the ruler asks Jesus to lay his hand on his daughter for her revival.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 59, 5, 14, 16, 'prayed, and laid his hands on him', 'Healing Through Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the act of prayer in healing the sick. In Acts, Paul prays and lays hands on the sick, while James instructs the elders to pray over the sick for healing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 40, 10, 8, 8, NULL, 'Healing Ministry of Paul', 'This connection highlights the act of healing as a key aspect of ministry in both passages. In Acts, Paul heals the sick, which parallels the command in Matthew to ''heal the sick.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 41, 16, 18, 18, 'laid his hands on him', 'Healing Through Laying on Hands', 'This connection highlights the act of laying hands on the sick, as seen in both passages. In Acts 28:8, Paul heals Publius by laying hands on him, which parallels the promise in Mark 16:18 that believers shall lay hands on the sick and they shall recover.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 8, 42, 13, 13, 13, 'laid his hands on him', 'Healing Through Laying on Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands as a means of healing. In each instance, the laying on of hands results in immediate restoration and glorification of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 9, 40, 4, 24, 24, 'were healed', 'Healing of the Sick', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of those with diseases. Acts 28:9 describes the healing of many on the island, paralleling Matthew 4:24''s account of Jesus healing various sick individuals. This connection highlights the theme of healing in both narratives.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 9, 41, 6, 54, 56, 'were healed', 'Healing Miracles of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the sick. In Acts, those with diseases were healed, while in Mark, many sought to touch Jesus for healing. This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 9, 44, 5, 12, 12, 'were healed', 'Healing and Signs Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the sick through the apostles'' ministry. Acts 28:9 describes healing on the island, while Acts 5:12 highlights signs and wonders performed by the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 9, 44, 5, 15, 15, 'were healed', 'Healing Miracles in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the sick through the apostles'' actions. In Acts 28:9, many were healed on the island, while in Acts 5:15, the sick were brought to Peter for healing. This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing in the early church.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 52, 2, 6, 6, 'honoured us with many honours', 'Honour and Burdensomeness Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of honour and the avoidance of being burdensome. Both passages address the reception of honour and the choice to not seek glory or impose on others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 40, 6, 31, 34, 'such things as were necessary', 'Provision and Trust in God', 'Both passages emphasize the provision of necessary things. Acts 28:10 mentions being ''laded...with such things as were necessary,'' while Matthew 6:31-34 reassures believers that their needs will be met if they seek God''s kingdom first.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 50, 4, 11, 12, 'such things as were necessary', 'Contentment in Provision', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being content regardless of circumstances. Acts 28:10 mentions being provided with necessary things, while Philippians 4:11-12 speaks of learning to be content in various states of need and abundance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 50, 4, 19, 19, 'such things as were necessary', 'Provision and Supply Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of God providing for needs. In Acts 28:10, the phrase ''such things as were necessary'' reflects the idea of provision, which is echoed in Philippians 4:19 where God promises to supply all needs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 12, 8, 9, 9, 'honoured us with many honours', 'Gifts and Honours in Context', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bringing gifts as a sign of respect and honor. In Acts, the people honored Paul and his companions, while in 2 Kings, Hazael brings a present to Elisha, indicating a similar cultural practice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 15, 7, 27, 27, 'honoured us with many honours', 'Honoring and Provision Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of honor and provision. In Acts, the people honored Paul and his companions with necessary things, while in Ezra, the king''s heart is moved to beautify the house of the Lord, indicating a provision for God''s work.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 10, 40, 10, 8, 10, 'laded us with such things as were necessary', 'Provision and Generosity in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of receiving and giving provisions in ministry. Acts 28:10 highlights being honored and provided for, while Matthew 10:8-10 instructs to travel without excess provisions, trusting in the generosity of others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 44, 27, 6, 6, 'ship of Alexandria', 'Connection of Ships in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a ship of Alexandria, indicating the journey of Paul. This connection highlights the continuity of travel and the significance of the ship in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 23, 45, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Deliverance and Idolatry', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from peril in Acts and the call to assemble away from idolatry in Isaiah. Both passages emphasize the importance of turning away from false gods and recognizing true salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 46, 8, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Idols and Symbols', 'This connection highlights the theme of symbols and their significance. In Acts, the mention of Castor and Pollux as symbols reflects the cultural context of idols, which is further addressed in 1 Corinthians regarding the nature of idols.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 32, 1, 5, 5, NULL, 'Mariners and Ship Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mariners in distress aboard a ship. In Acts, the ship is identified by its sign, while in Jonah, the mariners are afraid and take action to save themselves. This connection highlights the perilous situations faced by those at sea.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 32, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Fear and Divine Intervention', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and reverence towards God in both passages. In Acts, the ship''s journey signifies divine protection, while in Jonah, the men''s fear leads to worship and vows, emphasizing a response to divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 11, 44, 6, 9, 9, 'Alexandria', 'Connection through Alexandria', 'Both passages mention Alexandria, linking the ship''s journey to the diverse groups in the synagogue. This connection highlights the significance of Alexandria in the early Christian context.', 'keyword', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 13, 44, 27, 13, 13, 'south wind blew', 'Connection of Sailing Directions', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the south wind in the journey. The south wind''s influence is pivotal in both instances, guiding the sailors'' decisions and movements.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 1, 7, 4, 4, 'seven days', 'Seven Days of Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of a seven-day period of waiting or preparation in both passages. In Acts, the brethren desired to tarry for seven days, while in Genesis, God commands a seven-day wait before the flood begins.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 1, 8, 10, 12, 'seven days', 'Connection of Seven Days', 'Both passages emphasize a period of seven days, highlighting a significant waiting period. In Acts, the seven days represent fellowship before a journey, while in Genesis, they mark Noah''s careful observation of the flood''s receding.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 44, 19, 1, 1, 'found brethren', 'Connection through Travel and Fellowship', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s travels and interactions with believers. In Acts 28:14, Paul finds brethren and stays with them, while in Acts 19:1, he finds certain disciples in Ephesus. This connection highlights the theme of community among early Christians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 44, 20, 6, 6, 'seven days', 'Journey to Rome and Troas', 'Both passages emphasize a seven-day stay, highlighting the importance of fellowship during travel. The mention of ''seven days'' in both contexts connects the experiences of the early Christians as they journeyed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 19, 119, 63, 63, 'brethren', 'Connection of Companionship in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of companionship among believers. Both passages emphasize the importance of being with those who fear God and keep His precepts.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 40, 10, 11, 11, NULL, 'Hospitality and Community', 'This connection highlights the importance of finding worthy individuals in a community and staying with them. Both passages emphasize the act of abiding with others during a journey.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 14, 43, 21, 23, 23, 'tarry with them seven days', 'Connection of Brethren and Tarrying', 'This connection highlights the theme of fellowship among believers, as both passages mention the desire to ''tarry'' or stay with brethren. The emphasis on community and shared faith is evident in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 58, 13, 3, 3, 'whom when Paul saw, he thanked God', 'Connection of Suffering and Support', 'This connection highlights the theme of mutual support among believers. In Acts, Paul is encouraged by the brethren''s visit, while Hebrews calls for remembering those in bonds, emphasizing solidarity in suffering.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 45, 15, 24, 24, NULL, 'Paul''s Journey and Fellowship', 'This connection highlights Paul''s desire for fellowship and support during his travels. In both passages, Paul expresses gratitude and seeks companionship as he journeys to Spain and meets brethren.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 2, 4, 14, 14, 'whom when Paul saw, he thanked God', 'Meeting of Brothers', 'This connection highlights the theme of brothers meeting in both passages. In Acts, Paul is met by brethren who bring him encouragement, while in Exodus, Aaron comes to meet Moses, bringing joy to his heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 6, 1, 6, 7, 'took courage', 'Courage in Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of courage in leadership. In Acts, Paul takes courage upon meeting the brethren, while in Joshua, the call to be strong and courageous is central to leading the people into their inheritance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 9, 30, 6, 6, 'took courage', 'Encouragement in Distress', 'This connection highlights the theme of encouragement in times of distress. Both Paul and David find strength and courage through their faith amidst challenging circumstances.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 19, 27, 14, 14, 'took courage', 'Courage and Strength in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of courage and the strength that comes from faith in God. In Acts, Paul thanks God and takes courage upon meeting the brethren, while Psalms encourages waiting on the Lord to receive strength and courage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 15, 43, 12, 13, 13, NULL, 'Meeting and Acclamation', 'This connection highlights the theme of people coming to meet someone significant. Both passages emphasize the act of gathering and expressing joy or reverence upon meeting.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 44, 27, 3, 3, NULL, 'Paul''s Liberty in Custody', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s unique treatment while in custody. In Acts 27:3, Julius gives Paul liberty, while in Acts 28:16, Paul is allowed to dwell by himself with a soldier.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 44, 24, 23, 23, 'Paul was suffered to dwell by himself', 'Paul''s Liberty in Custody', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s ability to dwell by himself and have liberty while under guard. This connection highlights the consistent treatment of Paul, allowing him some freedom despite being a prisoner.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 45, 1, 7, 15, 'to dwell by himself with a soldier', 'Connection Between Paul and Rome', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s presence in Rome and his desire to connect with the believers there. Acts describes Paul''s arrival and situation, while Romans expresses his longing to visit and impart spiritual gifts to the saints in Rome.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 1, 37, 36, 36, 'captain of the guard', 'Connection of Captains of the Guard', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a ''captain of the guard'' in their narratives. This connection highlights the authority figures overseeing Paul and Joseph, linking their experiences of confinement and protection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 1, 39, 21, 23, 'suffered to dwell by himself', 'Divine Favor in Confinement', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of divine favor in confinement, as Paul is allowed to dwell by himself, similar to how Joseph is given favor by the keeper of the prison. This connection highlights the presence of God''s mercy and the resulting authority granted to both figures despite their imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 12, 25, 8, 8, 'captain of the guard', 'Connection of Captains of the Guard', 'This connection highlights the role of the captain of the guard in both passages. In Acts, Paul is under the watch of a soldier, while in 2 Kings, Nebuzar–adan serves as captain of the guard in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 16, 24, 40, 2, 2, 'captain of the guard', 'Connection of Captains of the Guard', 'This connection highlights the role of the captain of the guard in both passages. Both Paul and Jeremiah are under the authority of a captain, indicating a shared experience of confinement and oversight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 17, 44, 25, 8, 8, 'nothing against the people, or customs', 'Paul''s Defense Against Accusations', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s assertion of innocence regarding Jewish law and customs. In Acts 28:17, Paul states he has committed nothing against the people or customs, paralleling his earlier claim in Acts 25:8 that he has not offended against the law of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 17, 44, 6, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Accusations Against Paul', 'This connection highlights the accusations against Paul regarding his teachings. Both passages reference the idea of changing customs, with Acts 6:14 accusing Jesus of altering the customs of Moses, while Acts 28:17 defends Paul against similar charges.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 17, 44, 21, 33, 40, NULL, 'Paul''s Defense and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s identity as a Jew and his defense against accusations. In Acts 28, Paul asserts he has committed nothing against the customs of his people, paralleling his earlier defense in Acts 21 where he identifies himself as a Jew of Tarsus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 17, 44, 22, 5, 5, 'delivered prisoner from Jerusalem', 'Paul''s Defense of His Actions', 'This connection highlights Paul''s defense regarding his actions in Jerusalem. Both passages emphasize his role as a prisoner and his previous mission to bring bound individuals to Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 17, 1, 40, 15, 15, NULL, 'Innocence in Imprisonment', 'This connection highlights the theme of innocence in both passages. Paul asserts he has committed nothing against the people, while Joseph claims he has done nothing deserving of punishment.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 26, 31, 32, 'no cause of death in me', 'Paul''s Innocence and Release', 'Both passages emphasize that Paul was found innocent, with no cause for death. The acknowledgment of his lack of wrongdoing in Acts 26:31-32 directly supports his statement in Acts 28:18 about being examined and found without cause.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 23, 29, 29, 'no cause of death in me', 'Accusations of Worthiness', 'Both passages emphasize that there was no cause of death in Paul. This connection highlights the legal assessments made regarding his accusations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 22, 24, 25, 'no cause of death in me', 'Examination and Roman Citizenship', 'Both passages emphasize the examination of Paul and his status as a Roman citizen. In Acts 28:18, Paul notes there was ''no cause of death in me,'' while Acts 22:24-25 highlights the unlawful nature of his scourging as an uncondemned Roman.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 22, 30, 30, 'examined me', 'Paul''s Examination and Accusation', 'This connection highlights the examination of Paul in both passages. Acts 28:18 mentions his examination leading to a lack of cause for death, while Acts 22:30 discusses the examination to understand the accusations against him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 24, 10, 10, NULL, 'Paul''s Defense and Examination', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s defense before authorities. In Acts 28:18, Paul notes there was no cause for death, while in Acts 24:10, he addresses the governor directly, indicating his willingness to defend himself.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 24, 22, 22, 'examined me', 'Examination and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the process of examination regarding Paul’s case. In Acts 28:18, Paul notes he was examined and found without cause for death, while Acts 24:22 shows Felix deferring judgment until further examination by Lysias.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 18, 44, 25, 7, 8, 'no cause of death in me', 'Paul''s Innocence in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s lack of wrongdoing. In Acts 28:18, Paul states there was ''no cause of death in me,'' which aligns with the claims in Acts 25:7-8 that the accusations against him were unproven.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 44, 26, 32, 32, 'appeal unto Cesar', 'Paul''s Appeal to Caesar', 'This connection highlights Paul''s appeal to Caesar as a pivotal moment in his trial. Both passages emphasize the consequences of this appeal, with Acts 28:19 showing his reasoning and Acts 26:32 noting its impact on his potential freedom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 44, 25, 10, 12, NULL, 'Paul''s Appeal to Caesar', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s appeal unto Caesar as a legal recourse against accusations from the Jews. This connection highlights his assertion of innocence and the right to be judged by Roman authorities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 44, 25, 21, 21, 'appeal unto Cesar', 'Paul''s Appeal to Caesar', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s appeal to Caesar, highlighting his legal strategy in the face of opposition. This connection illustrates the continuity of Paul''s situation as he navigates the Roman legal system.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 44, 25, 25, 25, 'appeal unto Cesar', 'Appeal to Caesar Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of appealing to Caesar. In Acts 28:19, the speaker mentions being constrained to appeal to Caesar, while Acts 25:25 notes that he himself hath appealed to Augustus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 60, 2, 22, 23, 'not that I had ought to accuse my nation of', 'Response to Suffering and Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of unjust suffering and the response to revilement. Both passages emphasize a commitment to righteousness despite being wronged, as seen in the appeal to Caesar and the example of Christ''s response to suffering.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 19, 45, 12, 19, 21, NULL, 'Response to Wrongs', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to opposition without seeking personal vengeance. Both passages emphasize overcoming evil with good and trusting in divine justice.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 44, 26, 6, 7, 'hope of Israel', 'Connection of Hope in Israel', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hope related to Israel and God''s promises. In Acts 28:20, Paul speaks of being bound for ''the hope of Israel,'' while in Acts 26:6-7, he refers to being judged for ''the hope of the promise made of God.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 49, 6, 20, 20, 'I am bound with this chain', 'Ambassadorship and Chains', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being bound or in chains for the sake of the Gospel. They highlight the role of the speaker as an ambassador, advocating for the hope of Israel and speaking boldly despite imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 55, 2, 9, 9, 'I am bound with this chain', 'Connection of Suffering and Hope', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for the sake of the Gospel. Both passages emphasize being bound or in chains, yet affirm the enduring nature of God''s word.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 44, 26, 29, 29, 'bound with this chain', 'Connection of Paul''s Chains', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s bonds as a symbol of his commitment to the hope of Israel. The mention of being ''bound'' in both verses highlights his dedication despite his imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 50, 1, 13, 13, 'bound with this chain', 'Connection of Bonds and Hope', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being bound or in chains for a cause. Acts 28:20 mentions being bound for the hope of Israel, while Philippians 1:13 refers to bonds in Christ, suggesting a shared theme of imprisonment linked to faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 49, 3, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Paul''s Imprisonment', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s status as a prisoner. In Acts, he is bound for the hope of Israel, while in Ephesians, he identifies himself as a prisoner for the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 20, 57, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Bonds and Hope', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being bound or in chains. In Acts, Paul mentions being bound for the hope of Israel, while in Philemon, he refers to Onesimus as someone he has begotten in his bonds.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 21, 23, 41, 11, 11, NULL, 'Shame and Confounding of Enemies', 'This connection highlights the theme of those who oppose the faithful being ultimately ashamed and confounded. In Acts, the absence of accusations against Paul reflects the idea that those who strive against him will not succeed, paralleling Isaiah''s assurance that adversaries will perish.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 21, 23, 50, 8, 8, NULL, 'Justification and Adversaries', 'This connection highlights the theme of justification and the presence of adversaries. In Acts, the absence of accusations against Paul parallels the challenge posed in Isaiah to adversaries, emphasizing a defense against contention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 21, 23, 54, 17, 17, 'any harm of thee', 'Protection from Harm', 'This connection highlights the assurance of safety in both passages. Acts 28:21 indicates that no harm was spoken against Paul, while Isaiah 54:17 promises that no weapon formed against the servants of the Lord shall prosper.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 21, 44, 22, 5, 5, 'letters', 'Letters and Testimony Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of letters and testimony regarding Paul. In Acts 28:21, the absence of letters contrasts with Acts 22:5, where Paul mentions receiving letters from the high priest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 21, 2, 11, 7, 7, NULL, 'Divine Protection and Distinction', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine protection over God''s people. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the distinction made by God between His chosen people and others, as seen in the lack of harm reported in Acts and the protection described in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 44, 24, 14, 14, 'this sect, we know that every where it is spoken against', 'Connection of Heresy and Sect', 'Both passages emphasize the perception of the early Christian movement as controversial. Acts 28:22 refers to the sect being ''spoken against,'' while Acts 24:14 mentions the ''way which they call heresy.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 60, 2, 12, 12, 'spoken against', 'Response to Opposition', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of being spoken against. Acts 28:22 mentions that the sect is ''spoken against,'' while 1 Peter 2:12 refers to being ''speak against you as evildoers.'' This connection highlights the challenge faced by believers and the call to respond with good works.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 60, 3, 16, 16, 'spoken against', 'Connection of Suffering and Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of being spoken against and falsely accused. Both passages emphasize the experience of believers facing opposition and the importance of maintaining a good conscience amidst such challenges.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 44, 16, 20, 21, 'spoken against', 'Opposition to Early Christianity', 'Both passages emphasize the negative perception of early Christians. In Acts 28:22, the sect is spoken against, while Acts 16:20-21 describes how they trouble the city and teach unlawful customs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 42, 2, 34, 34, 'spoken against', 'Connection of Opposition to Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''spoken against.'' Acts 28:22 refers to a sect that faces opposition, while Luke 2:34 mentions a child who will be a sign that is also ''spoken against.'' This connection highlights the consistent presence of resistance to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 22, 46, 11, 19, 19, 'this sect', 'Connection of Sect and Heresies', 'This connection highlights the idea of division within the community. Both passages emphasize the presence of opposition and differing beliefs, with ''this sect'' in Acts and ''heresies'' in Corinthians indicating conflict among followers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 44, 17, 2, 3, 'persuading them concerning Jesus', 'Connection of Paul''s Teaching Method', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s approach of reasoning from the scriptures to persuade others about Jesus. In Acts 28, he expounds on the kingdom of God using the law of Moses and the prophets, similar to how he reasons from the scriptures in Acts 17.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 44, 19, 8, 8, 'the kingdom of God', 'Connection on Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of ''the kingdom of God'' and the act of persuading others about it. They illustrate the commitment of the apostles to teach and discuss this central message over extended periods.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 42, 24, 26, 27, 'expounded and testified the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Scriptural Exposition', 'Both passages emphasize the act of expounding from the law of Moses and the prophets regarding Jesus. This connection highlights the continuity of scriptural interpretation in understanding Christ''s role.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 42, 24, 44, 44, 'law of Moses, and out of the prophets', 'Connection of Law and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the law of Moses and the prophets in relation to Jesus. Acts 28:23 discusses persuading concerning Jesus from these texts, while Luke 24:44 states that all things must be fulfilled from them concerning Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 43, 4, 34, 34, NULL, 'Connection of Purpose and Work', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfilling God''s will. In Acts, Paul expounds on the kingdom of God, while in John, Jesus emphasizes doing the will of God. Both passages reflect a commitment to God''s mission.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 23, 57, 1, 2, 2, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection through Community and Fellowship', 'This connection highlights the communal aspect of faith, as both passages reference gatherings of believers. Acts 28:23 mentions ''the kingdom of God,'' which is central to the fellowship described in Philemon 1:2.', 'theme', 0.293, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'some believed not', 'Division in Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the division among people regarding belief. In Acts 28:24, some believed while others did not, paralleling the division in Acts 14:4 where part sided with the Jews and part with the apostles.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 44, 17, 4, 5, 'some believed', 'Belief and Unbelief Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the division between those who believed and those who did not. Acts 28:24 states, ''some believed'' while Acts 17:4-5 describes a similar scenario where ''some of them believed'' and others opposed them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 44, 19, 8, 9, 'some believed not', 'Belief and Rejection Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the division between those who believed and those who did not. In Acts 28:24, some believed while others rejected the message, mirroring the response in Acts 19:8-9 where some were hardened and believed not.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 44, 18, 6, 8, 'some believed the things which were spoken', 'Belief and Rejection Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the division between those who believe and those who do not. In Acts 28:24, some believed while others rejected the message, paralleling Acts 18:6-8 where opposition is met with belief from Crispus and others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 45, 3, 3, 3, 'some believed not', 'Connection of Belief and Unbelief', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief and unbelief. Acts 28:24 notes that some believed and some did not, while Romans 3:3 questions whether unbelief affects God''s faithfulness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 24, 45, 11, 4, 6, 'some believed the things which were spoken', 'Belief and Remnant Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the division between belief and unbelief. Acts 28:24 highlights the response of some who believed, while Romans 11:4-6 speaks of a remnant chosen by grace, illustrating God''s preservation of faith amidst disbelief.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 25, 40, 15, 7, 7, 'Well spake the Holy Ghost by Esaias', 'Connection of Prophecy and Hypocrisy', 'This connection highlights the role of Esaias as a prophet who speaks against hypocrisy. Both passages reference Esaias'' prophetic words, emphasizing the importance of his message to the people.', 'prophecy', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 25, 41, 7, 6, 6, 'Well spake the Holy Ghost by Esaias', 'Prophetic Warning of Hypocrisy', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in worship. Both passages emphasize the idea that outward expressions of honor do not reflect true devotion to God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 25, 61, 1, 21, 21, 'Well spake the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Prophetic Inspiration', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Ghost in inspiring prophets. Both passages emphasize that the words spoken by prophets are divinely guided rather than originating from human will.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 23, 6, 9, 10, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand', 'Connection of Hearing and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hearing without understanding and seeing without perceiving. This connection highlights the spiritual blindness and deafness of the people addressed in both texts.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 26, 12, 2, 2, NULL, 'Rebellion and Spiritual Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness among a rebellious people. They highlight the inability to hear and see the truth despite having the faculties to do so.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 23, 42, 19, 20, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand', 'Blindness and Hearing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness and deafness. Acts 28:26 echoes Isaiah 42:19-20 by highlighting the inability to perceive and understand despite being given the message.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 40, 13, 14, 15, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand', 'Connection of Prophetic Fulfillment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hearing and not understanding, highlighting the spiritual blindness of the people. The repetition of the phrase ''hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand'' underscores this connection.', 'prophecy', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 41, 4, 12, 12, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand; and seeing ye shall see, and not perceive', 'Connection of Hearing and Seeing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of people hearing and seeing but failing to understand or perceive. This connection highlights the idea of spiritual blindness and deafness to the message being conveyed.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 42, 24, 45, 45, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand', 'Understanding and Perception', 'This connection highlights the contrast between not understanding in Acts and the opening of understanding in Luke. Both passages emphasize the theme of comprehension in relation to hearing and seeing.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 26, 47, 4, 4, 6, 'Hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand', 'Spiritual Blindness and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness preventing understanding of the gospel. Acts 28:26 highlights the inability to perceive, while 2 Corinthians 4:4 discusses how the god of this world blinds minds to the light of Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 27, 23, 6, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the dullness of the people''s hearts and senses, indicating a spiritual blindness that prevents understanding and healing. The similar phrasing underscores a shared theme of rejection and the consequences of closed hearts.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 42, 2, 30, 32, 'salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles', 'Salvation for the Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of salvation being offered to the Gentiles. Acts 28:28 states that the salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, while Luke 2:32 describes a light to lighten the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 44, 26, 17, 18, 'salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles', 'Salvation Sent to Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the mission to the Gentiles, highlighting God''s intention for their salvation. Acts 28:28 states that the salvation of God is sent to the Gentiles, while Acts 26:17-18 describes the sending of Paul to open their eyes and lead them to God.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 42, 3, 6, 6, 'salvation of God', 'Connection of Salvation in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of salvation being available to all people. Acts 28:28 highlights that Gentiles will hear God''s salvation, while Luke 3:6 states that all flesh shall see it.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 45, 3, 29, 30, 'salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles', 'Salvation for Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan for salvation. Acts 28:28 states that salvation is sent to the Gentiles, while Romans 3:29-30 affirms that God justifies both Jews and Gentiles through faith.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 45, 15, 8, 16, 'salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles', 'Salvation for the Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s salvation plan. Acts 28:28 states that the salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, while Romans 15:8-16 discusses how Gentiles will glorify God for His mercy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 44, 11, 18, 18, 'salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles', 'Salvation Granted to Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize God''s outreach to the Gentiles. Acts 28:28 states that salvation is sent to the Gentiles, while Acts 11:18 acknowledges that God has granted them repentance unto life.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 28, 23, 52, 10, 10, 'salvation of God', 'Connection of Salvation to Nations', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of salvation being extended to all nations. Acts 28:28 highlights that the Gentiles will hear the salvation of God, while Isaiah 52:10 proclaims that all the ends of the earth shall see the salvation of our God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 31, 44, 4, 29, 29, 'with all confidence', 'Boldness in Preaching', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of boldness in proclaiming God''s message. Acts 28:31 highlights preaching with confidence, while Acts 4:29 requests boldness to speak God''s word.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 28, 31, 49, 6, 19, 20, 'with all confidence', 'Boldness in Proclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of boldness in proclaiming the gospel. Acts 28:31 speaks of preaching with confidence, while Ephesians 6:19-20 expresses a desire to speak boldly about the mystery of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
